<P>
JUST RELEASED IN PAPER: FICTION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
THE QUEEN OF THE DAMNED by Anne Rice (Ballantine: $5.95). Rice breathes life 
into the majestic Akasha, who awakens from a 6,000-year slumber to challenge 
Lestat, in this third installment of the vampire chronicles. 
</P>
<P>
FINAL FLIGHT by Stephens Coonts (Dell: $5.95). Capt. Jake Grafton of "The 
Flight of the Intruder" transfers to an aircraft carrier stalked by Arabs 
seeking its nuclear weapons. 
</P>
<P>
THE ANNA PAPERS by Ellen Gilchrist (Little, Brown: $8.95). At her funeral, 
family, friends and lovers ponder the suicide of successful and attractive 
writer Anna Hand. 
</P>
<P>
SO WORTHY MY LOVE by Kathleen E. Woodiwiss (Avon: $10.95). Errors and 
subterfuge result in a romantic encounter between two members of warring 
families. 
</P>
<P>
S. by John Updike (Fawcett Crest: $4.95). Diary of a suburban doctor's wife who 
sends missives on her way to an Arizona ashram. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
NONFICTION 
</P>
<P>
THE QUEEN OF MEAN: The Unauthorized Biography of Leona Helmsley by Ransdell 
Pierson (Bantam: $4.95). Pierson's initial investigation of the Helmsleys was 
the first salvo in a legal assault that led to the current indictments. 
</P>
<P>
ONE OF THE GUYS: The Wising Up Of An American Man by Harry Stein (Pocket: 
$7.95). Stein, through the process of self-examination, interviews and research 
provides a portrait of the evolving, contemporary American male. 
</P>
<P>
DON'T BEND OVER IN THE GARDEN GRANNY, YOU KNOW THEM TATERS GOT EYES by Lewis 
Grizzard (Ballantine: $4.95). Southern humorist's reflections on the mating 
habits, foibles, miscalculations and myths. 
</P>
<P>
LIMITS TO FRIENDSHIP: The United States and Mexico by Robert A. Pastor and 
Jorge G. Castaneda (Vintage: $10.95). Authors examine the social, political, 
and economic issues that overlap between these two countries. 
</P>
<P>
YOU COULD LOOK IT UP by William Safire (Holt: $12.95). These pensive essays on 
the peculiarities of English originated in Pulitzer Prize-winning Safire's 
column, "On Language" for the New York Times. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
SELF-HELP / REFERENCEWINNING MOVES by Jane Ciabattari (Penguin: $8.95). 
Surviving shake-downs which may be the result of a new boss, merger or 
restructuring within your organization. 
</P>
<P>
MAKING SENSE OF ADOPTION: A Parent's Guide by Lois Ruskai Melina (Perennial: 
$8.95). Second book on the subject of adoption includes the issues of 
birthparents, revealing troubling information, surrogate parenting and in vitro 
fertilization. 
</P>
