<HEADLINE>
<P>
HAMMER HINTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This is in reference to the article, "Tooling Up: A Rookie's Guide on What to 
Buy" (Sept. 3). 
</P>
<P>
The author, Charlyne Varkonyi of the Baltimore Sun, put forward some misleading 
and potentially dangerous recommendations concerning the purchase of a hammer. 
</P>
<P>
Varkonyi states, "Look for a cast rather than forged-steel claw hammer of 
smoothly polished steel. . . ." 
</P>
<P>
Fortunately, I doubt that any consumer would be able to find a hammer with a 
cast head. Any good hammer is always drop-forged steel. Cast metal breaks 
easily and can send chips flying. Forging is a process that strengthens steel 
and is necessary for any tool subject to stress and pounding, such as a claw 
hammer. 
</P>
<P>
I find it hard to believe that Michael DiMenna, owner of Schumann Hardware in 
Baltimore, who is quoted by Varkonyi, would tell her to select a cast rather 
than a forged hammer. She must have lost something in the translation. 
</P>
<P>
EARL A. WORCESTER 
</P>
<P>
Alhambra 
</P>
<P>
Editor's note: The letter writers are correct: Forged-steel claw hammers are 
safer than cast types. Varkonyi reports that the information on hammers was 
transposed in the article. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
