<HEADLINE>
<P>
SUSPECT ARRESTED IN HIT-AND-RUN THAT KILLED 3 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By NANCY RAY, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
National City police, with the help of telephone tips, arrested a 22-year-old 
San Diego man Saturday night on suspicion of three hit-and-run homicides. 
</P>
<P>
Pablo Salvador Cabrera was caught after a short freeway chase south on 
Interstate 5 after he had been spotted in Clairemont. 
</P>
<P>
Lt. Bill Osburn said that National City police had received numerous calls 
since the Thursday hit-and-run accident in which a pregnant National City woman 
and her 5-year-old daughter were struck and killed while crossing East 18th 
Street. 
</P>
<P>
Martha Lidia Zamudio, 25, was about eight months pregnant when she and her 
daughter, Lili Beth Zamudio, were struck by a tan station wagon and dragged a 
short distance before the driver sped away. Attempts to save the unborn baby 
were unsuccessful. 
</P>
<P>
Cabrera and a cousin, Luis Padilla, 18, of Riverside, were spotted by four 
National special response teams as the pair pulled out of a gas station near 
Clairemont Mesa Boulevard and Balboa Avenue about 7 p.m. Saturday night, Osburn 
said. 
</P>
<P>
Two of the unmarked police cars chased and attempted to stop the car driven by 
Padilla as it headed south on Interstate 5. The arrest was made near the Front 
Street exit in downtown San Diego, after "we stuck a gun in his face" and 
forced the Cabrera car to a halt, Osburn said. 
</P>
<P>
Padilla was released after questioning. Osburn said Padilla said he was not 
aware of the hit-and-run incident when he responded to a call from Cabrera to 
come to San Diego. 
</P>
<P>
The Riverside man tried to convince Cabrera to give himself up to police when 
the National City officers spotted the pair in Clairemont, Osburn said. 
</P>
<P>
Earlier, police had contacted Cabrera by telephone and arranged for him to give 
himself up. But Cabrera did not appear at the agreed-upon meeting place. 
</P>
<P>
Cabrera was booked into County Jail in downtown San Diego on suspicion of three 
counts of motor vehicle homicide, one count of felony hit-and-run and driving 
on a suspended driver's license. 
</P>
</TEXT>
