<HEADLINE>
<P>
HIGH SCHOOL FOOTBALL ROUNDUP; 
</P>
<P>
WHITTIER CHRISTIAN DOWNS BELL-JEFF 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEFF RILEY In another game: Faith Baptist 23, Flintridge Prep 6 -- Alex 
Estrada had 11 carries for 146 yards 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Whittier Christian's Ron Papazian and Scott Jordan combined for 188 yards and 
four touchdowns in a nonleague game against Bellarmine-Jefferson on Saturday at 
Burroughs High. 
</P>
<P>
Then they played the second half. 
</P>
<P>
When it finally ended, Jordan -- a hard-running tailback -- had 203 yards in 23 
carries. Papazian, a 6-foot-2, 200-pound fullback, carried 20 times for 142 
yards and five touchdowns. And Whittier Christian, 4-0 and ranked third in the 
Division IX poll, accumulated more real estate than Donald Trump in a 42-0 win. 
</P>
<P>
"We were a little surprised the offense executed so well," Whittier Coach Phil 
Bravo said. "We moved the ball pretty good." 
</P>
<P>
About the only manner in which Whittier might have moved the ball any better 
would have been to toss the football into the back of a Chevy and put it in 
overdrive. Whittier Christian was in fourth gear all night, gaining 399 rushing 
yards (7.1 yards a carry), 423 total yards and 18 first downs. 
</P>
<P>
"They completely manhandled us," Bell-Jeff Coach Doug Woodlief said. 
</P>
<P>
Whittier led, 28-0, at the half after four touchdown runs from Papazian, then 
added two more scores in the third quarter -- on a 46-yard scamper by Papazian 
and a two-yard run by Jordan. 
</P>
<P>
Jordan missed last week's game because of a bruised collarbone. 
</P>
<P>
How bad was it for Bell-Jeff? Whittier Christian faced first and 50 from its 
24, then scored three plays later. 
</P>
<P>
The Whittier defense, meanwhile, limited Bell-Jeff to 48 total yards (31 
rushing in 20 carries) and three first downs. Bell-Jeff (0-3-1) had only nine 
total yards at the half and possession for five of the half's 24 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
"We were even more surprised with our defense," Bravo said. "(The defense) 
performed well in crucial times." 
</P>
<P>
But Saturday night, the only crucial moment was the opening coin flip -- which 
Whittier Christian also won. JEFF RILEY In another game: Faith Baptist 23, 
Flintridge Prep 6 -- Alex Estrada had 11 carries for 146 yards and made a key 
interception for Faith Baptist in an eight-man game at Flintridge Prep. 
Estrada's interception on the one-yard line in the second quarter preserved a 
15-0 halftime lead. Quarterback Gavin Amos, who scored both first-half 
touchdowns on runs of two and one yard, had 10 carries for 33 yards and was 
five of 13 passing for 128 yards. Amos hit Steve Roe with a 69-yard scoring 
pass early in the fourth quarter. Quarterback Chris Bisgaard scored on a 
one-yard run in the fourth quarter for the only Flintridge Prep touchdown. 
</P>
</TEXT>
