1819 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
'DO YOU HAVE A TABLE FOR TWO AT 8?' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RUTH REICHL 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The restaurant business, people in the business will tell you, is terrible. 
They blame it on the stock market, on the baby boom, on the changes in the tax 
laws. 
</P>
<P>
But our almost-annual survey tells a different story. Every year or so we sit 
down at 4 o'clock on Friday afternoon and call restaurants all over town asking 
for a table for two at 8 that night. 
</P>
<P>
The first time we did it we discovered that tables were available in all the 
top of the line expensive restaurants while the hip new grills and cafes simply 
laughed at the notion that a table might be available on such short notice. A 
year and a half ago things were different: At 4 o'clock on a Friday afternoon 
not a single restaurant in town turned us down. While many did not have a table 
at 8, most were able to accommodate us between 7:30 and 8:30. 
</P>
<P>
Things have changed. These days if you want to make last minute plans for the 
weekend, you'd best be prepared for dinner at 6 or 10, because that's when a 
lot of local restaurants are going to ask you to eat. If you've got your eye on 
Saturday, things get even worse: only a quarter of the restaurants we called on 
Friday were able to offer us a Saturday night table at a reasonable hour. 
</P>
<P>
Other than reaffirming the fact that Los Angeles loves a new restaurant (and 
especially a new and reasonable restaurant), few patterns emerged. The top of 
the line expensive restaurants are doing well, old favorites are doing well, 
new favorites are thriving. Los Angeles restaurants, in fact, are cooking. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
NEW (Open 18 months or less) 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
RESTAURANT: Brentwood Bar and Grill, 11647 San Vicente Blvd., Brentwood, 
820-2121 
</P>
<P>
AVAILABLE FRIDAY?: No. "But if you smoke, I can take you at 8:30, otherwise 
8:45." 
</P>
<P>
AVAILABLE SATURDAY?: No. 6:45 or 8:45 
</P>
