<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE NATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
North Carolina has refused the Ku Klux Klan permission to join an 
Adopt-a-Highway cleanup program that would have allowed the group to post its 
name on signs along a stretch of road running through a black neighborhood. 
Under the program, the state puts up eye-catching, green-and-white road signs 
naming the group or business that has pledged to clean the adopted stretch of 
road four times a year. The klan asked for a 3.4-mile stretch of road on U.S. 
158 in Rockingham County about 100 miles from Raleigh through a predominantly 
black neighborhood. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
KU KLUX KLAN; BEAUTIFICATION; SIGNS; GOVERNMENT REGULATION; NORTH CAROLINA -- 
LAWS; RACIAL RELATIONS -- NORTH CAROLINA 
</P>
